{"title_page": "Canadian Security Intelligence Service", "text_new": "{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name     = Canadian Security Intelligence Service\n|nativename_a    =\n|nativename_r    =\n|logo            = Canadian Security Intelligence Service logo.svg\n|logo_width      = 325 px\n|logo_caption    =\n|seal            =\n|seal_width      = \n|seal_caption    = Badge of the Canadian Security Intelligence Service\n|formed          = June 21, 1984, by [[Act of Parliament#Canada|Act of Parliament]] \n|preceding1      = [[RCMP Security Service]]\n|preceding2      =\n|dissolved       =\n|superseding     =\n|jurisdiction    =\n|headquarters    = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n|employees       = 5,500<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/23958185/A-Study-Into-the-Size-of-the-World-s-Intelligence-Industry|title=A Study Into the Size of the World\u2019s Intelligence Industry (Master's Thesis, December 2009), 87|website=scribd.com}}</ref>\n|budget          = C$1 billion<ref>https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2016/02/23/canadas-spies-expecting-a-budget-boost.html</ref>\n|minister1_name  = [[The Honourable]] [[Bill Blair (politician)|Bill Blair]]\n|minister1_pfo   = [[Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness]]\n|minister2_name  =\n|minister2_pfo   =\n|chief1_name     = David Vigneault\n|chief1_position = Director\n|chief2_name     =\n|chief2_position =\n|parent_agency   = [[Public Safety Canada]]\n|child1_agency   =\n|child2_agency   =\n|website         = [https://www.canada.ca/en/security-intelligence-service.html CSIS]\n|footnotes       =\n|chief3_name=|chief3_position=|chief4_name=|chief4_position=|chief5_name=|chief5_position=|chief6_name=|chief6_position=|chief7_name=|chief7_position=|chief8_name=|chief8_position=|chief9_name=|chief9_position=|parent_department=}}\n\nThe '''Canadian Security Intelligence Service''' ('''CSIS''', {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|i\u02d0|s|\u026a|s}}; {{lang-fr|Service canadien du renseignement de s\u00e9curit\u00e9}}, ''SCRS'') is [[Canada]]'s primary national [[intelligence service]]. It is responsible for collecting, analysing, reporting and disseminating [[Intelligence assessment|intelligence]] on threats to Canada's [[national security]], and conducting operations, [[covert operation|covert]] and overt, [[Security agency|within]] Canada and abroad.<ref name=\"CSISWEB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/bts/rlfcss-eng.asp |title=Role of CSIS |publisher=Csis-scrs.gc.ca |date=2009-04-09 |accessdate=2010-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226011438/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/bts/rlfcss-eng.asp# |archive-date=2010-12-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It also reports to and advises the [[Government of Canada]] on national security issues and situations that threaten the security of the nation.\n\nIts headquarters are located in [[Ottawa]] in a purpose-built facility completed in 1995.<ref>[http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/domino/reports.nsf/html/9608ce.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060221035839/http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/domino/reports.nsf/html/9608ce.html|date=February 21, 2006}}</ref>  CSIS is responsible to [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]] through the [[Minister of Public Safety]], but is also overseen by the [[Federal Court (Canada)|Federal Court]] and the [[National Security and Intelligence Review Agency]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/en/about_us/accountability.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070426180642/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/en/about_us/accountability.asp |archivedate=2007-04-26 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nPrior to 1984 security intelligence in Canada was the purview of the [[RCMP Security Service|Royal Canadian Mounted Police Security Service]]. However, in the 1970s there were allegations that the RCMP Security Service had been involved in numerous illegal activities. As a result of these allegations, in 1977, Justice David Macdonald was appointed to investigate the activities of RCMP Security Service. The resulting investigation, known as the [[Royal Commission of Inquiry into Certain Activities of the RCMP|McDonald Commission]], published its final report in 1981, with its main recommendation being that security intelligence work should be separated from policing, and that a civilian intelligence agency be created to take over from the RCMP Security Service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ps-sp.gc.ca/prg/ns/airs/rep1-4-eng.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080629115242/http://www.ps-sp.gc.ca/prg/ns/airs/rep1-4-eng.aspx |archivedate=2008-06-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 1984, CSIS was created by an [[Parliament of Canada|Act of Parliament]]. At the time it was also decided that the activities of this new agency, the Canadian Security Intelligence Service, should be subject to both judicial approval for warrants, as well as general review by a new body, the [[Security Intelligence Review Committee]], as well as the office of the Inspector General (which was disbanded in 2012). Its ''[[de facto]]'' existence began on July 16 under the direction of [[Ted Finn|Thomas D'Arcy Finn]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/en/about_us/history_artifacts/history/brf_csis_index.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070624182416/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/en/about_us/history_artifacts/history/brf_csis_index.asp |archivedate=2007-06-24 }}</ref>\n\nAt first, the main emphasis of CSIS was combating the activities of various foreign intelligence agencies operating in Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/hstrrtfcts/rtfcts/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601021026/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/hstrrtfcts/rtfcts/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-06-01 }}</ref> For example, it has been engaged in investigating economic espionage involving Chinese operations throughout Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/story.html?id=ca90416e-fe77-4b8d-ae59-a4e9f55b6441&k=26688 |title=Government vows to curb Chinese spying on Canada |publisher=Canada.com |date=2006-04-16 |accessdate=2011-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004005118/http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/story.html?id=ca90416e-fe77-4b8d-ae59-a4e9f55b6441&k=26688# |archive-date=2014-10-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While the threat posed by foreign intelligence agencies still remain, CSIS over the years has focused more and more on the threat to Canadian security and its citizens posed by terrorist activity.\n\n==Insignia==\n\nCSIS is one of several  [[Heraldic badges of the Canadian government|federal departments]] (primarily those involved with law enforcement, security, or having a regulatory function) that has been granted a heraldic badge. The badge was created in July 1984 (pre-dating the creation of the [[Canadian Heraldic Authority]]), and received Royal approval in June 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reg.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project-pic.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=1109&ProjectImageID=1435|title=Canadian Security Intelligence Service [Civil Institution]|first=The Office of the Secretary to the Governor|last=General|website=reg.gg.ca}}</ref>\n\nOn December 21, 2016, a CSIS flag was raised for the first time by the Director at the national headquarters. The flag displays the CSIS badge on a white field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/security-intelligence-service/news/2016/12/csis_director_statementregardingtheraisingofthecsisflags.html|title=CSIS Director Statement regarding the raising of the CSIS flags|first=Canadian Security Intelligence|last=Service|date=December 21, 2016|website=gcnws}}</ref>\n\n==Mission and operations==\n\nCSIS is Canada's lead agency on [[national security]] matters and for conducting national security investigations and security intelligence collection. CSIS collects, analyzes intelligence, advises the Government of Canada on issues and activities that may threaten the security of Canada and its citizens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121229074654/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-12-29 }}</ref>  These threats include terrorism,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/trrrsm/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327040929/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/trrrsm/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2013-03-27 }}</ref> espionage and foreign interference in Canadian affairs,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/spng/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121227094020/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/spng/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-12-27 }}</ref> proliferation of weapons of mass destruction,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/prlfrtn/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019182941/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/prlfrtn/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-10-19 }}</ref> and information security threats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/nfrmtn/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224015805/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/nfrmtn/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2013-02-24 }}</ref> The agency is also responsible for the security screening program.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/scrt-scrnng-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228204748/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/scrt-scrnng-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-12-28 }}</ref>\n\nThere is no restriction in the CSIS Act on where CSIS may collect \"security intelligence\" or information relating to threats to the security of Canada. The agency may collect information on threats to Canada or Canadians from anywhere in the world. While CSIS is often viewed as a defensive ''security intelligence'' agency, it is not a domestic agency. CSIS officers work partly domestically and most often internationally in their efforts to monitor and counter threats to Canadian security.\n\nThere is a distinction between \"security intelligence\" and \"foreign intelligence\". Security intelligence pertains to national security threats (e.g., [[terrorism]], [[espionage]]). Foreign intelligence involves information collection relating to the political or economic activities of foreign states. Previous law stated that CSIS was only allowed to collect this intelligence  within Canada but with updated law in 2016 they are now allowed to collect That intelligence abroad as well. Since 2016 Most domestic on the ground tasks are handed over to the RCMP.\n\nCSIS has served in many different countries, especially after 9/11. Examples of some of the countries they have served in are: Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Lebanon, Mali, Libya, Sudan, Pakistan, Somalia, Qatar, Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates.       \n\nCSIS is neither a police agency nor is it a part of the military. As an intelligence agency, the primary role of CSIS is not law enforcement. Investigation of criminal activity is left to the RCMP and local (provincial, regional or municipal) police agencies. CSIS, like counterparts such as the [[United Kingdom]] Security Service ([[MI5]]) and the United States [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA), is a civilian agency. CSIS is subject to review by the Security Intelligence Review Committee (SIRC) as well as other legislative checks and balances. The agency carries out its functions in accordance with the CSIS Act, which governs and defines its powers and activities.\n\nCanadian police, military agencies (see [[Intelligence Branch (Canadian Forces)|Canadian Forces Intelligence Branch]]), and numerous other government departments may maintain their own \"intelligence\" components (i.e. to analyze criminal intelligence or military strategic intelligence). The [[Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade]] maintains a Security and Intelligence Bureau to review and analyze overtly acquired information.  The bureau plays a coordinating and policy role. While not an intelligence agency, it is responsible for the security of Department of Foreign Affairs personnel around the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stenotran.com/commission/maherarar/2005-05-17%20volume%2011.pdf |title=P:\\Commissions of Inquiry\\Maher Arar\\2005-05-17 volume 11.wpd |format=PDF |accessdate=2010-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611110400/http://www.stenotran.com/commission/maherarar/2005-05-17%20volume%2011.pdf# |archive-date=2011-06-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, these agencies are not to be confused with the more encompassing work of larger, more dedicated \"intelligence agencies\" such as CSIS, MI5, [[MI6]], or the CIA.\n\nAs Canada's contributor of [[Human intelligence (intelligence gathering)|human intelligence]] to the [[Five Eyes]], CSIS works closely with the intelligence agencies of the [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Australia]], and [[New Zealand]]. Under the post\u2013World War II [[Quadripartite Agreement (1947)|Quadripartite (UKUSA) Agreement]], intelligence information is shared between the intelligence agencies of these five countries.\n\nPermission to put a subject under surveillance is granted by the [[Target Approval and Review Committee]].\n\n[[Security Liaison Officer]]s (SLOs) of CSIS are posted at Canadian embassies and consulates to gather security-related intelligence from other nations. This information may be gathered from other national intelligence agencies, law enforcement services and other sources. SLOs also assess potential immigrants to Canada for security issues.\n\nCSIS has been named one of \"[[Canada's Top 100 Employers]]\" by Mediacorp Canada Inc. for the years of 2009\u20132011, and was featured in ''[[Maclean's]]'' newsmagazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eluta.ca/jobs-at-csis|title=All jobs at Canadian Security Intelligence Service / CSIS &#124; Eluta.ca|website=www.eluta.ca}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n\n===Regional===\nCSIS headquarters is located in Ottawa, Ontario and is responsible for the overall operations. Regionally, Canada is broken down into six subordinate regions; the Atlantic, Quebec, Ottawa, Toronto, Prairie, and British Columbia Regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://csiscareers.ca/en/working-csis/work-environment/regional-offices|title=Regional Offices|work=csiscareers.ca|access-date=2013-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527075916/http://csiscareers.ca/en/working-csis/work-environment/regional-offices|archive-date=2013-05-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThese regions are responsible for investigating any threat to Canada and its allies as defined by the CSIS Act. They liaise with the various federal, provincial, municipal and private sector entities found within their areas of responsibility. They also conduct various outreach programs with different community and cultural groups, universities, and private sector organizations in an effort to provide a better understanding, and to clear up any misunderstandings of what CSIS' role is.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csis.gc.ca/pblctns/nnlrprt/2010-2011/rprt2010-2011-eng_final.asp#cooperation |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116141304/https://www.csis.gc.ca/pblctns/nnlrprt/2010-2011/rprt2010-2011-eng_final.asp |archivedate=2012-11-16 }}</ref> All these regions also border the United States and they therefore maintain contact with their U.S. federal counterparts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csis.gc.ca/pblctns/nnlrprt/2009-2010/rprt2009-2010-eng.asp#profile |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529174129/http://www.csis.gc.ca/pblctns/nnlrprt/2009-2010/rprt2009-2010-eng.asp |archivedate=2013-05-29 }}</ref>\n\n====Atlantic Region====\nThe Atlantic Region encompasses the four Atlantic provinces ([[Nova Scotia]], [[New Brunswick]], [[Newfoundland and Labrador]], and [[Prince Edward Island]] and is the smallest of the six CSIS regions. Its main office is located in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], with two district offices in [[Fredericton, NB|Fredericton]] and [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]].\n\n====Quebec Region====\nThis region is responsible solely for the province of [[Quebec]]. Its main office is in [[Montreal]], with one district office in [[Quebec City]].\n\n====Ottawa and Toronto Regions====\nThese two regions are responsible for operations in Ontario (except for NW Ontario). There are four district offices located in Niagara Falls, Windsor, [[Downtown Toronto]] and at [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/arrest-made-after-scare-outside-csis-offices-1.594759 |title=Arrest made after scare outside CSIS offices &#124; CTV Toronto News |website=Toronto.ctvnews.ca |date=2011-01-11 |accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref>\n\n====Prairie Region====\nGeographically, this represents the largest of the six regions and encompasses the area of Ontario north and west of [[Thunder Bay]], [[Manitoba]], [[Saskatchewan]], [[Alberta]] and the three northern territories of [[Yukon]], [[Northwest Territories]] and [[Nunavut]]. The regional office is located in [[Edmonton]] with three district offices located in [[Winnipeg]], [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] and [[Calgary]].\n\n====British Columbia====\nThis region is responsible for the province of British Columbia. Its main office is located in downtown Burnaby with a district office at the [[Vancouver International Airport]].\n\n===Branches===\nCSIS is functionally divided into four branches:<ref name=\"Lowenthal2016\">{{cite book|author=Mark M. Lowenthal|title=Intelligence: From Secrets to Policy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DiE9DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT410|date=29 September 2016|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-5063-7957-9|page=410}}</ref>\n\n* Counter-Intelligence\n* Counter-Proliferation\n* Counterterrorism\n* Research, Analysis and Production (RAP)\n\n==Equipment== \n* [[CH-147 Chinook]] (Loaned from Canadian Forces)\n* [[CH-146 Griffon]]\n* [[IAI Searcher]]\n* [[Chevrolet Equinox]] \n* [[Chevrolet Express]]\n* [[Ford Taurus]]\n* [[Chevrolet Tahoe]]\n* [[Land Rover Defender]]\n\n==Weapons==\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 5906]]{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* [[C8 Carbine]]<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/undercover-csis-agents-carry-guns-in-foreign-flashpoints/article4320423/</ref>\n====Research, Analysis and Production====\nThe RAP was reorganized in 1996-1997 in order to better coordinate with the Intelligence Assessment Secretariat of the [[Privy Council Office (Canada)|Privy Council Office]].<ref name=\"book1\">{{cite book|title=Inside Canadian Intelligence: Exposing the New Realities of Espionage and International Terrorism|url=https://archive.org/details/insidecanadianin00hami|url-access=registration|date=30 May 2011|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=978-1-55488-891-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/insidecanadianin00hami/page/40 40]}}</ref><ref name=\"Lowenthal2016\"/> It has four sub-divisions: Counter Intelligence, Foreign Intelligence, Counter-terrorism and Distribution.<ref name=\"book1\"/>\n\n==Oversight==\nAs part of an omnibus national security bill passed by Parliament in 2019, the oversight and reporting regime for CSIS was overhauled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/services/defence/nationalsecurity/our-security-our-rights/enhancing-accountability-transparency.html|title=Enhancing Accountability and Transparency|last=Canada|first=Public Safety|date=2017-11-22|website=aem|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> The previous agency that handled all oversight of CSIS, the [[Security Intelligence Review Committee]] (SIRC) was replaced by a new agency, the [[National Security and Intelligence Review Agency|National Security & Intelligence Review Agency]] (NSIRA), which now includes oversight of all national security and intelligence activities undertaken by any agency of the Government of Canada.\n\nThe reforms also include the creation of a new [[Intelligence Commissioner of Canada|Intelligence Commissioner]] who reports to Parliament and has quasi-judifical oversight of all national security matters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/intelligence-commissioner.html|title=Office of the Intelligence Commissioner|last=Commissioner|first=Office of the Intelligence|date=2019-07-17|website=aem|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> \n\n==Controversies==\n{{Global surveillance}}\n{{POV section|date=April 2013}}\nIn several instances, CSIS has been accused of misrepresenting facts to the Courts.<ref name=\"Ottawa Citizen\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/canada-involved-in-us-spying-efforts-abroad-leaked-document-says/article15133508/ |title=CSIS asked foreign agencies to spy on Canadians, kept court in dark, judge says by Ian MacLeod |date= 20 December 2013 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[Ottawa Citizen]] }}</ref> In 2013, CSIS was censured by Federal Court Judge [[Richard Mosley]] for deliberately misleading Canada's Federal Court to make it possible for them to allow other agencies to spy on Canadians abroad, which is not allowed by Canadian law.<ref>{{cite news |first=Colin |last=Perkel |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/canada/judge-slams-spy-agency-for-end-running-law-to--intercept-canadians-abroad-236781891.html |title=Judge slams spy agency for end-running law to intercept Canadians abroad |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |date=20 December 2013 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] }}</ref> \"Justice Mosley has found that CSIS breached its duty of candour to the Court by not disclosing information that was relevant,\" the Federal Court stated in a press release.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/csis-not-being-forthcoming-with-court-federal-judge-says/article15599674/ |title=CSIS not being forthcoming with court, federal judge says by Colin Freeze |date=25 November 2013 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] }}</ref>\n\nCSIS has also been involved in cases where evidence has been mishandled or omitted from the Courts. In 2009, it was alleged that the service did not disclose information that their confidential informants, which CSIS had been relying on to gather information about their targets, were either deceptive,{{clarify|date=October 2014}} or failed lie-detector tests.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2009/06/30/spy_agency_bungled_second_terror_case.html |title=Spy agency bungled second terror case by Michelle Shephard |date=30 June 2009 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[Toronto Star]] }}</ref> This was not an isolated case, and in several other instances, the agency mishandling of evidence has also called for investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2009/06/30/spy_agency_bungled_second_terror_case.html |title=Failed lie detector test casts doubt on Harkat terror case by Andrew Duffy, Canwest News Service |date=5 June 2009 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[National Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2009/06/30/spy_agency_bungled_second_terror_case.html |title=CSIS failed to give judge info on Almrei |date=30 June 2009 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref>\n\nCSIS has, at times, come under criticism,{{by whom|date=October 2014}} such as for its role in the investigation of the 1985 [[Air India Flight 182|Air India bombing]]. The Commission of Inquiry into the Investigation of the Bombing of Air India Flight 182, headed by Justice John Major, is underway. Two Canadian courts have publicly criticized CSIS for destroying [[wiretap]] evidence. One court impressed upon the importance of wiretap evidence from CSIS in establishing guilt. The second focused on its [[exculpatory]] value.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nFrom 1988 to 1994, CSIS mole [[Grant Bristow]] infiltrated the Canadian white-supremacist movement.  When the story became public knowledge, the press aired concerns that he had not only been one of the founders of the [[Heritage Front]] group, but that he had also channelled CSIS funding to the group.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/28/world/canada-s-security-agency-accused-of-spying-on-canadians.html|title=Canada's Security Agency Accused of Spying on Canadians|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref>\n\nOn September 18, 2006, the Arar Commission absolved CSIS of any involvement in the [[extraordinary rendition]] by the United States of a [[Canadians|Canadian]] citizen, [[Maher Arar]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} The Commission found that U.S. authorities sent Arar to [[Jordan]] and then [[Syria]] (his country of birth) based on incorrect information which had been provided by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) to the U.S. government. Arar was held by the Syrians for one year and was tortured. The sole criticism of CSIS leveled by the Commission was that the agency should do more to critically examine information provided by regimes which practice [[torture]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}\n\nOn March 31, 2009, CSIS lawyer and advisor Geoffrey O'Brian told the [[House of Commons of Canada Standing Committee on Public Safety and National Security|Committee on Public Safety and National Security]] that CSIS would use information obtained by torture if it could prevent another attack such as [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] or the Air India bombing. Testifying before the same committee two days later, Director of CSIS Jim Judd said that O'Brian \"may have been confused\" and \"venturing into a hypothetical\", and would send the committee a clarifying letter.<ref>{{cite news |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |url=https://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/612514 |title=Official misspoke; CSIS says it's not involved in torture |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2009-04-02 |accessdate=2011-03-02}}</ref> Two weeks later CSIS announced that Judd would be retiring in June, five months before the end of his five-year term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/618623 |title=Head of CSIS stepping down |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2009-04-15 |accessdate=2011-03-02}}</ref>\n\nCSIS has come under attack on a number of occasions for what is seen by some as very aggressive tactics.  A vociferous critic of the Service, Lawyer [[Faisal Kutty]], writes as follows:  \"Showing up at homes and workplaces unannounced; speaking with employers; offering money and favors for \"information\"; intimidating and threatening newcomers; questioning about specific institutions and individuals; inquiring about a person's religiosity; and discouraging people from engaging lawyers are some of the recurring themes that I have come across from clients. The problem is so severe that the Council on American Islamic Relations (Canada) has distributed almost 30,000 Know Your Rights guides and organized 27 workshops across the country on dealing with the Canadian Security Intelligence Service (CSIS) and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP).\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2004/04/28/the-dirty-work-of-canadian-intelligence/|title=The Dirty Work of Canadian Intelligence |work=[[CounterPunch]] |date=April 28, 2004 |accessdate=2012-11-16}}</ref>\n\nProminent Canadian national security lawyer [[Barbara Jackman]] has also been critical, categorizing the research by CSIS as \"sloppy\" and that its officers are \"susceptible to [[tunnel vision]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2006/09/12/jaballah-certificate.html|title=Defence challenges CSIS intelligence in security certificate case |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=September 12, 2006 |accessdate=2012-11-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, several CSIS members accused the organization of having a racist and homophobic workplace culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idCAKBN19Z22D-OCADN|title=Canadian spies accuse bosses of homophobia, racism: lawsuit|first=David|last=Ljunggren|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n* [[Canada Border Services Agency]]\n* [[Canadian Cyber Incident Response Centre]]\n* [[Communications Security Establishment]]\n* [[Financial Transactions and Reports Analysis Centre of Canada]]\n* [[Intelligence Branch (Canadian Forces)]]\n*[[National Security and Intelligence Review Agency|National Security & Intelligence Review Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca }}\n*[http://circ.jmellon.com/agencies/csis/ CSIS news archive at The Canadian Intelligence Resource Centre (CIRC)]\n*[http://www.parl.gc.ca/infocomdoc/38/1/snsn/meetings/evidence/snsnev15-e.htm 38th PARLIAMENT, 1st SESSION] contains a review about CSIS's and RCMP's role under the Anti-Terrorism Act\n{{Coord|45.4374|-75.614|type:landmark_region:CA|display=title}}\n\n{{Domestic national intelligence agencies}}\n\n{{Can Intel}}\n{{Government Departments of Canada}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian Security Intelligence Service| ]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian intelligence agencies|Security Intelligence Service]]\n[[Category:Canadian federal departments and agencies]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Public Safety Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Government agency\n|agency_name     = Canadian Security Intelligence Service\n|nativename_a    =\n|nativename_r    =\n|logo            = Canadian Security Intelligence Service logo.svg\n|logo_width      = 325 px\n|logo_caption    =\n|seal            =\n|seal_width      = \n|seal_caption    = Badge of the Canadian Security Intelligence Service\n|formed          = June 21, 1984, by [[Act of Parliament#Canada|Act of Parliament]] \n|preceding1      = [[RCMP Security Service]]\n|preceding2      =\n|dissolved       =\n|superseding     =\n|jurisdiction    =\n|headquarters    = [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n|employees       = 5,500<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/23958185/A-Study-Into-the-Size-of-the-World-s-Intelligence-Industry|title=A Study Into the Size of the World\u2019s Intelligence Industry (Master's Thesis, December 2009), 87|website=scribd.com}}</ref>\n|budget          = C$1 billion<ref>https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2016/02/23/canadas-spies-expecting-a-budget-boost.html</ref>\n|minister1_name  = [[The Honourable]] [[Bill Blair (politician)|Bill Blair]]\n|minister1_pfo   = [[Minister of Public Safety and Emergency Preparedness]]\n|minister2_name  =\n|minister2_pfo   =\n|chief1_name     = David Vigneault\n|chief1_position = Director\n|chief2_name     =\n|chief2_position =\n|parent_agency   = [[Public Safety Canada]]\n|child1_agency   =\n|child2_agency   =\n|website         = [https://www.canada.ca/en/security-intelligence-service.html CSIS]\n|footnotes       =\n|chief3_name=|chief3_position=|chief4_name=|chief4_position=|chief5_name=|chief5_position=|chief6_name=|chief6_position=|chief7_name=|chief7_position=|chief8_name=|chief8_position=|chief9_name=|chief9_position=|parent_department=}}\n\nThe '''Canadian Security Intelligence Service''' ('''CSIS''', {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|i\u02d0|s|\u026a|s}}; {{lang-fr|Service canadien du renseignement de s\u00e9curit\u00e9}}, ''SCRS'') is [[Canada]]'s primary national [[intelligence service]]. It is responsible for collecting, analysing, reporting and disseminating [[Intelligence assessment|intelligence]] on threats to Canada's [[national security]], and conducting operations, [[covert operation|covert]] and overt, [[Security agency|within]] Canada and abroad.<ref name=\"CSISWEB\">{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/bts/rlfcss-eng.asp |title=Role of CSIS |publisher=Csis-scrs.gc.ca |date=2009-04-09 |accessdate=2010-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101226011438/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/bts/rlfcss-eng.asp# |archive-date=2010-12-26 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It also reports to and advises the [[Government of Canada]] on national security issues and situations that threaten the security of the nation.\n\nIts headquarters are located in [[Ottawa]] in a purpose-built facility completed in 1995.<ref>[http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/domino/reports.nsf/html/9608ce.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060221035839/http://www.oag-bvg.gc.ca/domino/reports.nsf/html/9608ce.html|date=February 21, 2006}}</ref>  CSIS is responsible to [[Parliament of Canada|Parliament]] through the [[Minister of Public Safety]], but is also overseen by the [[Federal Court (Canada)|Federal Court]] and the [[National Security and Intelligence Review Agency]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/en/about_us/accountability.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070426180642/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/en/about_us/accountability.asp |archivedate=2007-04-26 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nPrior to 1984 security intelligence in Canada was the purview of the [[RCMP Security Service|Royal Canadian Mounted Police Security Service]]. However, in the 1970s there were allegations that the RCMP Security Service had been involved in numerous illegal activities. As a result of these allegations, in 1977, Justice David Macdonald was appointed to investigate the activities of RCMP Security Service. The resulting investigation, known as the [[Royal Commission of Inquiry into Certain Activities of the RCMP|McDonald Commission]], published its final report in 1981, with its main recommendation being that security intelligence work should be separated from policing, and that a civilian intelligence agency be created to take over from the RCMP Security Service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ps-sp.gc.ca/prg/ns/airs/rep1-4-eng.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2008-03-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080629115242/http://www.ps-sp.gc.ca/prg/ns/airs/rep1-4-eng.aspx |archivedate=2008-06-29 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 1984, CSIS was created by an [[Parliament of Canada|Act of Parliament]]. At the time it was also decided that the activities of this new agency, the Canadian Security Intelligence Service, should be subject to both judicial approval for warrants, as well as general review by a new body, the [[Security Intelligence Review Committee]], as well as the office of the Inspector General (which was disbanded in 2012). Its ''[[de facto]]'' existence began on July 16 under the direction of [[Ted Finn|Thomas D'Arcy Finn]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/en/about_us/history_artifacts/history/brf_csis_index.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-05-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070624182416/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/en/about_us/history_artifacts/history/brf_csis_index.asp |archivedate=2007-06-24 }}</ref>\n\nAt first, the main emphasis of CSIS was combating the activities of various foreign intelligence agencies operating in Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/hstrrtfcts/rtfcts/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-07-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601021026/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/hstrrtfcts/rtfcts/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-06-01 }}</ref> For example, it has been engaged in investigating economic espionage involving Chinese operations throughout Canada.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/story.html?id=ca90416e-fe77-4b8d-ae59-a4e9f55b6441&k=26688 |title=Government vows to curb Chinese spying on Canada |publisher=Canada.com |date=2006-04-16 |accessdate=2011-03-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004005118/http://www.canada.com/montrealgazette/news/story.html?id=ca90416e-fe77-4b8d-ae59-a4e9f55b6441&k=26688# |archive-date=2014-10-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> While the threat posed by foreign intelligence agencies still remain, CSIS over the years has focused more and more on the threat to Canadian security and its citizens posed by terrorist activity.\n\n==Insignia==\n\nCSIS is one of several  [[Heraldic badges of the Canadian government|federal departments]] (primarily those involved with law enforcement, security, or having a regulatory function) that has been granted a heraldic badge. The badge was created in July 1984 (pre-dating the creation of the [[Canadian Heraldic Authority]]), and received Royal approval in June 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://reg.gg.ca/heraldry/pub-reg/project-pic.asp?lang=e&ProjectID=1109&ProjectImageID=1435|title=Canadian Security Intelligence Service [Civil Institution]|first=The Office of the Secretary to the Governor|last=General|website=reg.gg.ca}}</ref>\n\nOn December 21, 2016, a CSIS flag was raised for the first time by the Director at the national headquarters. The flag displays the CSIS badge on a white field.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/security-intelligence-service/news/2016/12/csis_director_statementregardingtheraisingofthecsisflags.html|title=CSIS Director Statement regarding the raising of the CSIS flags|first=Canadian Security Intelligence|last=Service|date=December 21, 2016|website=gcnws}}</ref>\n\n==Mission and operations==\n\nCSIS is Canada's lead agency on [[national security]] matters and for conducting national security investigations and security intelligence collection. CSIS collects, analyzes intelligence, advises the Government of Canada on issues and activities that may threaten the security of Canada and its citizens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121229074654/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-12-29 }}</ref>  These threats include terrorism,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/trrrsm/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130327040929/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/trrrsm/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2013-03-27 }}</ref> espionage and foreign interference in Canadian affairs,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/spng/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121227094020/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/spng/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-12-27 }}</ref> proliferation of weapons of mass destruction,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/prlfrtn/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121019182941/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/prlfrtn/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-10-19 }}</ref> and information security threats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/nfrmtn/index-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224015805/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/nfrmtn/index-eng.asp |archivedate=2013-02-24 }}</ref> The agency is also responsible for the security screening program.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/scrt-scrnng-eng.asp |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-01-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121228204748/http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca/prrts/scrt-scrnng-eng.asp |archivedate=2012-12-28 }}</ref>\n\nThere is no restriction in the CSIS Act on where CSIS may collect \"security intelligence\" or information relating to threats to the security of Canada. The agency may collect information on threats to Canada or Canadians from anywhere in the world. While CSIS is often viewed as a defensive ''security intelligence'' agency, it is not a domestic agency. CSIS officers work partly domestically and most often internationally in their efforts to monitor and counter threats to Canadian security.\n\nThere is a distinction between \"security intelligence\" and \"foreign intelligence\". Security intelligence pertains to national security threats (e.g., [[terrorism]], [[espionage]]). Foreign intelligence involves information collection relating to the political or economic activities of foreign states. Previous law stated that CSIS was only allowed to collect this intelligence  within Canada but with updated law in 2016 they are now allowed to collect That intelligence abroad as well. Since 2016 Most domestic on the ground tasks are handed over to the RCMP.\n\nCSIS has served in many different countries especially after 9/11 examples of some of the countries they have served in are: Afghanistan, Iraq, Syria, Lebanon, Mali, Libya, Sudan,Pakistan , Somalia, Qatar, Kuwait and United Arab Emirates.       \n\nCSIS is neither a police agency nor is it a part of the military. As an intelligence agency, the primary role of CSIS is not law enforcement. Investigation of criminal activity is left to the RCMP and local (provincial, regional or municipal) police agencies. CSIS, like counterparts such as the [[United Kingdom]] Security Service ([[MI5]]) and the United States [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA), is a civilian agency. CSIS is subject to review by the Security Intelligence Review Committee (SIRC) as well as other legislative checks and balances. The agency carries out its functions in accordance with the CSIS Act, which governs and defines its powers and activities.\n\nCanadian police, military agencies (see [[Intelligence Branch (Canadian Forces)|Canadian Forces Intelligence Branch]]), and numerous other government departments may maintain their own \"intelligence\" components (i.e. to analyze criminal intelligence or military strategic intelligence). The [[Department of Foreign Affairs and International Trade]] maintains a Security and Intelligence Bureau to review and analyze overtly acquired information.  The bureau plays a coordinating and policy role. While not an intelligence agency, it is responsible for the security of Department of Foreign Affairs personnel around the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stenotran.com/commission/maherarar/2005-05-17%20volume%2011.pdf |title=P:\\Commissions of Inquiry\\Maher Arar\\2005-05-17 volume 11.wpd |format=PDF |accessdate=2010-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611110400/http://www.stenotran.com/commission/maherarar/2005-05-17%20volume%2011.pdf# |archive-date=2011-06-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, these agencies are not to be confused with the more encompassing work of larger, more dedicated \"intelligence agencies\" such as CSIS, MI5, [[MI6]], or the CIA.\n\nAs Canada's contributor of [[Human intelligence (intelligence gathering)|human intelligence]] to the [[Five Eyes]], CSIS works closely with the intelligence agencies of the [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Australia]], and [[New Zealand]]. Under the post\u2013World War II [[Quadripartite Agreement (1947)|Quadripartite (UKUSA) Agreement]], intelligence information is shared between the intelligence agencies of these five countries.\n\nPermission to put a subject under surveillance is granted by the [[Target Approval and Review Committee]].\n\n[[Security Liaison Officer]]s (SLOs) of CSIS are posted at Canadian embassies and consulates to gather security-related intelligence from other nations. This information may be gathered from other national intelligence agencies, law enforcement services and other sources. SLOs also assess potential immigrants to Canada for security issues.\n\nCSIS has been named one of \"[[Canada's Top 100 Employers]]\" by Mediacorp Canada Inc. for the years of 2009\u20132011, and was featured in ''[[Maclean's]]'' newsmagazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eluta.ca/jobs-at-csis|title=All jobs at Canadian Security Intelligence Service / CSIS &#124; Eluta.ca|website=www.eluta.ca}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\n\n===Regional===\nCSIS headquarters is located in Ottawa, Ontario and is responsible for the overall operations. Regionally, Canada is broken down into six subordinate regions; the Atlantic, Quebec, Ottawa, Toronto, Prairie, and British Columbia Regions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://csiscareers.ca/en/working-csis/work-environment/regional-offices|title=Regional Offices|work=csiscareers.ca|access-date=2013-08-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527075916/http://csiscareers.ca/en/working-csis/work-environment/regional-offices|archive-date=2013-05-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThese regions are responsible for investigating any threat to Canada and its allies as defined by the CSIS Act. They liaise with the various federal, provincial, municipal and private sector entities found within their areas of responsibility. They also conduct various outreach programs with different community and cultural groups, universities, and private sector organizations in an effort to provide a better understanding, and to clear up any misunderstandings of what CSIS' role is.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csis.gc.ca/pblctns/nnlrprt/2010-2011/rprt2010-2011-eng_final.asp#cooperation |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121116141304/https://www.csis.gc.ca/pblctns/nnlrprt/2010-2011/rprt2010-2011-eng_final.asp |archivedate=2012-11-16 }}</ref> All these regions also border the United States and they therefore maintain contact with their U.S. federal counterparts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.csis.gc.ca/pblctns/nnlrprt/2009-2010/rprt2009-2010-eng.asp#profile |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-02-05 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529174129/http://www.csis.gc.ca/pblctns/nnlrprt/2009-2010/rprt2009-2010-eng.asp |archivedate=2013-05-29 }}</ref>\n\n====Atlantic Region====\nThe Atlantic Region encompasses the four Atlantic provinces ([[Nova Scotia]], [[New Brunswick]], [[Newfoundland and Labrador]], and [[Prince Edward Island]] and is the smallest of the six CSIS regions. Its main office is located in [[Halifax, Nova Scotia|Halifax]], with two district offices in [[Fredericton, NB|Fredericton]] and [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. John's]].\n\n====Quebec Region====\nThis region is responsible solely for the province of [[Quebec]]. Its main office is in [[Montreal]], with one district office in [[Quebec City]].\n\n====Ottawa and Toronto Regions====\nThese two regions are responsible for operations in Ontario (except for NW Ontario). There are four district offices located in Niagara Falls, Windsor, [[Downtown Toronto]] and at [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toronto.ctvnews.ca/arrest-made-after-scare-outside-csis-offices-1.594759 |title=Arrest made after scare outside CSIS offices &#124; CTV Toronto News |website=Toronto.ctvnews.ca |date=2011-01-11 |accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref>\n\n====Prairie Region====\nGeographically, this represents the largest of the six regions and encompasses the area of Ontario north and west of [[Thunder Bay]], [[Manitoba]], [[Saskatchewan]], [[Alberta]] and the three northern territories of [[Yukon]], [[Northwest Territories]] and [[Nunavut]]. The regional office is located in [[Edmonton]] with three district offices located in [[Winnipeg]], [[Regina, Saskatchewan|Regina]] and [[Calgary]].\n\n====British Columbia====\nThis region is responsible for the province of British Columbia. Its main office is located in downtown Burnaby with a district office at the [[Vancouver International Airport]].\n\n===Branches===\nCSIS is functionally divided into four branches:<ref name=\"Lowenthal2016\">{{cite book|author=Mark M. Lowenthal|title=Intelligence: From Secrets to Policy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DiE9DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT410|date=29 September 2016|publisher=SAGE Publications|isbn=978-1-5063-7957-9|page=410}}</ref>\n\n* Counter-Intelligence\n* Counter-Proliferation\n* Counterterrorism\n* Research, Analysis and Production (RAP)\n\n==Equipment== \n* [[CH-147 Chinook]] (Loaned from Canadian Forces)\n* [[CH-146 Griffon]]\n* [[IAI Searcher]]\n* [[Chevrolet Equinox]] \n* [[Chevrolet Express]]\n* [[Ford Taurus]]\n* [[Chevrolet Tahoe]]\n* [[Land Rover Defender]]\n\n==Weapons==\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 5906]]{{cn|date=March 2020}}\n* [[C8 Carbine]]<ref>https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/undercover-csis-agents-carry-guns-in-foreign-flashpoints/article4320423/</ref>\n====Research, Analysis and Production====\nThe RAP was reorganized in 1996-1997 in order to better coordinate with the Intelligence Assessment Secretariat of the [[Privy Council Office (Canada)|Privy Council Office]].<ref name=\"book1\">{{cite book|title=Inside Canadian Intelligence: Exposing the New Realities of Espionage and International Terrorism|url=https://archive.org/details/insidecanadianin00hami|url-access=registration|date=30 May 2011|publisher=Dundurn|isbn=978-1-55488-891-7|page=[https://archive.org/details/insidecanadianin00hami/page/40 40]}}</ref><ref name=\"Lowenthal2016\"/> It has four sub-divisions: Counter Intelligence, Foreign Intelligence, Counter-terrorism and Distribution.<ref name=\"book1\"/>\n\n==Oversight==\nAs part of an omnibus national security bill passed by Parliament in 2019, the oversight and reporting regime for CSIS was overhauled.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/services/defence/nationalsecurity/our-security-our-rights/enhancing-accountability-transparency.html|title=Enhancing Accountability and Transparency|last=Canada|first=Public Safety|date=2017-11-22|website=aem|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> The previous agency that handled all oversight of CSIS, the [[Security Intelligence Review Committee]] (SIRC) was replaced by a new agency, the [[National Security and Intelligence Review Agency|National Security & Intelligence Review Agency]] (NSIRA), which now includes oversight of all national security and intelligence activities undertaken by any agency of the Government of Canada.\n\nThe reforms also include the creation of a new [[Intelligence Commissioner of Canada|Intelligence Commissioner]] who reports to Parliament and has quasi-judifical oversight of all national security matters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/intelligence-commissioner.html|title=Office of the Intelligence Commissioner|last=Commissioner|first=Office of the Intelligence|date=2019-07-17|website=aem|access-date=2019-07-25}}</ref> \n\n==Controversies==\n{{Global surveillance}}\n{{POV section|date=April 2013}}\nIn several instances, CSIS has been accused of misrepresenting facts to the Courts.<ref name=\"Ottawa Citizen\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/canada-involved-in-us-spying-efforts-abroad-leaked-document-says/article15133508/ |title=CSIS asked foreign agencies to spy on Canadians, kept court in dark, judge says by Ian MacLeod |date= 20 December 2013 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[Ottawa Citizen]] }}</ref> In 2013, CSIS was censured by Federal Court Judge [[Richard Mosley]] for deliberately misleading Canada's Federal Court to make it possible for them to allow other agencies to spy on Canadians abroad, which is not allowed by Canadian law.<ref>{{cite news |first=Colin |last=Perkel |url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/canada/judge-slams-spy-agency-for-end-running-law-to--intercept-canadians-abroad-236781891.html |title=Judge slams spy agency for end-running law to intercept Canadians abroad |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |date=20 December 2013 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[Winnipeg Free Press]] }}</ref> \"Justice Mosley has found that CSIS breached its duty of candour to the Court by not disclosing information that was relevant,\" the Federal Court stated in a press release.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/csis-not-being-forthcoming-with-court-federal-judge-says/article15599674/ |title=CSIS not being forthcoming with court, federal judge says by Colin Freeze |date=25 November 2013 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] }}</ref>\n\nCSIS has also been involved in cases where evidence has been mishandled or omitted from the Courts. In 2009, it was alleged that the service did not disclose information that their confidential informants, which CSIS had been relying on to gather information about their targets, were either deceptive,{{clarify|date=October 2014}} or failed lie-detector tests.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2009/06/30/spy_agency_bungled_second_terror_case.html |title=Spy agency bungled second terror case by Michelle Shephard |date=30 June 2009 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[Toronto Star]] }}</ref> This was not an isolated case, and in several other instances, the agency mishandling of evidence has also called for investigation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2009/06/30/spy_agency_bungled_second_terror_case.html |title=Failed lie detector test casts doubt on Harkat terror case by Andrew Duffy, Canwest News Service |date=5 June 2009 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |work=[[National Post]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2009/06/30/spy_agency_bungled_second_terror_case.html |title=CSIS failed to give judge info on Almrei |date=30 June 2009 |accessdate=2014-03-11 |publisher=[[CBC News]]}}</ref>\n\nCSIS has, at times, come under criticism,{{by whom|date=October 2014}} such as for its role in the investigation of the 1985 [[Air India Flight 182|Air India bombing]]. The Commission of Inquiry into the Investigation of the Bombing of Air India Flight 182, headed by Justice John Major, is underway. Two Canadian courts have publicly criticized CSIS for destroying [[wiretap]] evidence. One court impressed upon the importance of wiretap evidence from CSIS in establishing guilt. The second focused on its [[exculpatory]] value.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nFrom 1988 to 1994, CSIS mole [[Grant Bristow]] infiltrated the Canadian white-supremacist movement.  When the story became public knowledge, the press aired concerns that he had not only been one of the founders of the [[Heritage Front]] group, but that he had also channelled CSIS funding to the group.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/08/28/world/canada-s-security-agency-accused-of-spying-on-canadians.html|title=Canada's Security Agency Accused of Spying on Canadians|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref>\n\nOn September 18, 2006, the Arar Commission absolved CSIS of any involvement in the [[extraordinary rendition]] by the United States of a [[Canadians|Canadian]] citizen, [[Maher Arar]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}} The Commission found that U.S. authorities sent Arar to [[Jordan]] and then [[Syria]] (his country of birth) based on incorrect information which had been provided by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] (RCMP) to the U.S. government. Arar was held by the Syrians for one year and was tortured. The sole criticism of CSIS leveled by the Commission was that the agency should do more to critically examine information provided by regimes which practice [[torture]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}\n\nOn March 31, 2009, CSIS lawyer and advisor Geoffrey O'Brian told the [[House of Commons of Canada Standing Committee on Public Safety and National Security|Committee on Public Safety and National Security]] that CSIS would use information obtained by torture if it could prevent another attack such as [[September 11 attacks|9/11]] or the Air India bombing. Testifying before the same committee two days later, Director of CSIS Jim Judd said that O'Brian \"may have been confused\" and \"venturing into a hypothetical\", and would send the committee a clarifying letter.<ref>{{cite news |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |url=https://www.thestar.com/News/Canada/article/612514 |title=Official misspoke; CSIS says it's not involved in torture |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2009-04-02 |accessdate=2011-03-02}}</ref> Two weeks later CSIS announced that Judd would be retiring in June, five months before the end of his five-year term.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/618623 |title=Head of CSIS stepping down |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=2009-04-15 |accessdate=2011-03-02}}</ref>\n\nCSIS has come under attack on a number of occasions for what is seen by some as very aggressive tactics.  A vociferous critic of the Service, Lawyer [[Faisal Kutty]], writes as follows:  \"Showing up at homes and workplaces unannounced; speaking with employers; offering money and favors for \"information\"; intimidating and threatening newcomers; questioning about specific institutions and individuals; inquiring about a person's religiosity; and discouraging people from engaging lawyers are some of the recurring themes that I have come across from clients. The problem is so severe that the Council on American Islamic Relations (Canada) has distributed almost 30,000 Know Your Rights guides and organized 27 workshops across the country on dealing with the Canadian Security Intelligence Service (CSIS) and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police (RCMP).\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.counterpunch.org/2004/04/28/the-dirty-work-of-canadian-intelligence/|title=The Dirty Work of Canadian Intelligence |work=[[CounterPunch]] |date=April 28, 2004 |accessdate=2012-11-16}}</ref>\n\nProminent Canadian national security lawyer [[Barbara Jackman]] has also been critical, categorizing the research by CSIS as \"sloppy\" and that its officers are \"susceptible to [[tunnel vision]]\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2006/09/12/jaballah-certificate.html|title=Defence challenges CSIS intelligence in security certificate case |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=September 12, 2006 |accessdate=2012-11-16}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, several CSIS members accused the organization of having a racist and homophobic workplace culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idCAKBN19Z22D-OCADN|title=Canadian spies accuse bosses of homophobia, racism: lawsuit|first=David|last=Ljunggren|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==<!-- PLEASE RESPECT ALPHABETICAL ORDER -->\n* [[Canada Border Services Agency]]\n* [[Canadian Cyber Incident Response Centre]]\n* [[Communications Security Establishment]]\n* [[Financial Transactions and Reports Analysis Centre of Canada]]\n* [[Intelligence Branch (Canadian Forces)]]\n*[[National Security and Intelligence Review Agency|National Security & Intelligence Review Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.csis-scrs.gc.ca }}\n*[http://circ.jmellon.com/agencies/csis/ CSIS news archive at The Canadian Intelligence Resource Centre (CIRC)]\n*[http://www.parl.gc.ca/infocomdoc/38/1/snsn/meetings/evidence/snsnev15-e.htm 38th PARLIAMENT, 1st SESSION] contains a review about CSIS's and RCMP's role under the Anti-Terrorism Act\n{{Coord|45.4374|-75.614|type:landmark_region:CA|display=title}}\n\n{{Domestic national intelligence agencies}}\n\n{{Can Intel}}\n{{Government Departments of Canada}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Canadian Security Intelligence Service| ]]\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Canada]]\n[[Category:Canadian intelligence agencies|Security Intelligence Service]]\n[[Category:Canadian federal departments and agencies]]\n[[Category:Government agencies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Public Safety Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Arkt005", "label": "safe", "comment": "I made a few spelling and grammar changes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canadian_Security_Intelligence_Service"}
{"title_page": "Tie the Knot", "text_new": "{{Short description|Thoroughbred racehorse}}\n\n{{about||the song by Jesse McCartney|In Technicolor|the song by Digital Underground|This Is an EP Release}}\n\n{{Infobox racehorse\n| horsename = Tie the Knot\n| image = \n| caption = \n| sire = [[Nassipour]] (USA)\n| grandsire = [[Blushing Groom]] (FR)\n| dam = Whisked (AUS)\n| damsire =  Whiskey Road (USA)\n| sex = [[Gelding]]\n| foaled = 1994\n| country = [[Australia]] \n| colour = [[Chestnut (coat)|Chestnut]]\n| breeder = Sandy Tait & Jill Nivison\n| owner = Sandy Tait & Jill Nivison\n| trainer = [[Guy Walter]]\n| record = 62: 21-9-8 \n| earnings =[[A$]]6,212,835<ref>[http://www.studbook.org.au/Horse.aspx?hid=576669 ASB: Tie The Knot] Retrieved 2009-10-6</ref>  \n| race =  [[Spring Champion Stakes]] (1997)<br>[[Rosehill Guineas]] (1998)<br>[[Sydney Cup]] (1998, 1999)<br>[[Underwood Stakes]] (1998)<br>[[Chipping Norton Stakes]] (1999, 2000, 2001, 2002)<br>[[The BMW Stakes]] (1999, 2000)<br>[[Ranvet Stakes]] (2000, 2001)\n| awards= [[Australian Champion Stayer]] (2000)\n| honours =  \n| updated= 6 October 2009\n}}\n\n'''Tie the Knot''' ([[foal]]ed 1994 - Died October 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://formguide.cyberhorse.com.au/2012102857176/Australia/Tie-The-Knot-Dies-Aged-18.html|title=Tie The Knot Dies Aged 18|publisher=Virtual Formguide|accessdate=28 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203213732/http://formguide.cyberhorse.com.au/2012102857176/Australia/Tie-The-Knot-Dies-Aged-18.html|archivedate=3 February 2016}}</ref> was an [[Australian]]-bred [[Thoroughbred]] [[racehorse]] who won 13 [[Group One]] races. In 1999-2000, he was voted [[Australian Champion Stayer]].\n\n==Breeding==\nTie the Knot was a chestnut gelding sired by [[Nassipour]] (USA) from Whisked by Whiskey Road (USA). Nassipour was also the sire of [[Let's Elope]] (NZ), who won the [[Melbourne Cup]], [[Mackinnon Stakes]] and [[Caulfield Cup]]. Tie the Knot was bred and raced by Mr O.P. Tait and Mrs S.S. Nivison. He was a half brother to the stakes winner Dream Ballad by Singspiel (IRE) and eight other named horses.<ref>[http://www.studbook.org.au/horse.aspx?hid=397109&pagetype=MAREBRDG ASB: Whisked] Retrieved 2009-10-6</ref>  Their dam, Whisked, won three group races and almost [[A$]]550,000, including the [[The Thousand Guineas|VATC One Thousand Guineas]]. She died on 29 September 2009 from complications after producing a live filly by Strategic.<ref>Land Newspaper, 2009-9-29, Rural Press, North Richmond, NSW</ref>\n\n==Racing career==\nTie the Knot won the [[Sydney Cup]] in both 1998 and 1999 and captured the Group one [[Chipping Norton Stakes]] in four consecutive years between 1999 and 2002.<ref>[http://www.news.com.au/dailytelegraph/story/0,22049,25382239-5006070,00.html Daily Telegraph - In the footsteps of a champion] Retrieved on 20 May 2009</ref>\n\nHe retired from racing with a record of 21 wins and 17 minor placings and earnings of A$6,212,835 from his 62 starts.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2002/04/02/1017206204750.html Tie The Knot off into sunset] Retrieved on 20 May 2009</ref> His total of 13 group one wins has been topped in Australasia only by Black Caviar's 15 wins, [[Kingston Town (horse)|Kingston Town]]'s 14 and is equal to [[Sunline]]'s. The only other horses to better his number of G1 wins are Winx [[John Henry (horse)|John Henry]] with 16 wins and [[Forego]] with 14 wins. His winnings in stake money places him behind Winx Redzel [[Makybe Diva]] (GB), [[Sunline]] (NZ) and [[Northerly]] on the all-time [[Australasia]]n list.\n\nTie the Knot was voted the 1999-2000 [[Australian Champion Stayer]].\n\n==Race record==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ 1996-97 season as a two year old\n|-\n!Result||Date||Race!!Venue!!Group!!Distance!!Weight (kg)!!Jockey!!Winner/2nd\n|-\n|5th||17 Jun 1997||2yo Hcp Restricted||[[Warwick Farm Racecourse|Warwick Farm]]||NA||1200 m||54||J. Sheehan||1st - Loophole\n|-\n|6th||09 Jul 1997||2